I'm little late but hope this helps I do my vocals a little differently, from recording the vocals I have a track that is just my mic being recorded, but it is not linked to the main track, it's being linked to a different track that will have the effects being used. I use this method to get a rough idea how I want the song to sound when I go in the finalizing. If I'm going to add effects such as reverb, or delay. I will put those on a different track, so if I want to turn off reverb or delay for certain bits I can do that with ease

BeanOwl 2025-01-17 4:29 PM
So for music production, any headphones/iems you want should be as flat response as possible. That essentially means the EQ curve should be close to flat/straight. Most consumer headphone companies these days like to “pre-EQ” their headphones so that it sounds “better” to the customer, but the problem with that is it creates inaccurate sound, meaning not the way the producer of whatever you’re listening to intended it to be heard. So in that sense, you want to find headphones that are intended for mixing/music production. I personally prefer iems(in ear monitors) for mixing, as I find I get a better bass response. I currently use the Letshouer S12 Pro’s, I really like their response and they sound match up perfectly to my HS5 studio monitors. If you wanna go over-the-ear, the best out there right now are the DT 900 Pro’s, though you’re paying for what you get for those. A good budget option is the ATH-M50x’s.
